{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_013BmUaUA52y5ewi7VkMYYvS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015dM1LRerTHYLNdnPcJz7vT","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cd /home/claude/workspace/repos/doublezero-edge-connect; gh api repos/malbeclabs/doublezero-edge-connect/pulls/29 2>&1 | python3 -c \"import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print('TITLE:',d['title']); print('BASE:',d['base']['ref']); print('HEAD:',d['head']['ref'],d['head']['sha']); print('UPDATED:',d['updated_at']); print('---BODY---'); print(d['body'])\" 2>&1 | head -120","description":"Get PR29 body via API"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3650,"cache_read_input_tokens":35265,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3650},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0e0cfeb0-baf3-4b7d-9735-46f33d7f33c8","uuid":"6fdf396e-fe3b-4f03-afc0-8108d0d0d001","request_id":"req_011Cc9zHBxP86tra4ievFnRq"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015dM1LRerTHYLNdnPcJz7vT","type":"tool_result","content":"TITLE: Multi-publisher TOB dedup (source-IP demux + windowed-identity)\nBASE: bdz/tob-pcap-fixtures\nHEAD: bdz/multi-publisher-dedup de61ad58f0268480853948599e468a6b8784926c\nUPDATED: 2026-06-18T02:54:13Z\n---BODY---\n## Summary\r\n\r\nMulti-publisher **Top-of-Book** deduplication: when several independent publishers mirror the same feed onto one multicast group, re-serve each logical update once, coherently ordered. **Stacked on #23** (base `bdz/tob-pcap-fixtures`); rebase to `main` once that merges. MBO depth dedup is tracked separately in #28.\r\n\r\n## What's included\r\n\r\n- **Source-IP demux.** The datagram source address (from `recvmsg`) is surfaced as `FrameCtx.publisher`. Stock publishers all use `channel_id = 0` with no per-publisher wire field, so source IP is the demux key (confirmed with the feed team).\r\n- **Per-source-IP `SeqTracker`.** Keyed by source IP so a slower publisher's frames aren't cross-dropped as \"stale\" before dedup runs.\r\n- **Quotes — latch-to-leader floor** (`src/ingest/arbiter.rs`, `StalenessFloor<K,V,P>`): per `(venue, symbol)`, within one `source_ts` tick emit only the *leader* (first publisher to open the tick) and drop other publishers' samples at that `source_ts`; re-select the leader each new tick. Also drops a strictly-older BBO (stale laggard) and the leader's exact `(source_ts, content)` repeats. Output `source_ts` is non-decreasing; within a tick the series is one publisher's coherent, in-order subsequence.\r\n- **Trades — windowed `trade_id` dedup** (`WindowedDedup`): a point-in-time event, so a competing publisher's copy / in-window reorder is dropped but every distinct print is kept.\r\n\r\n## Why latch-to-leader (not a merge floor)\r\n\r\nHL stamps `source_ts` coarsely — block-granular, up to ~376 distinct BBOs share one `source_ts` — so a tick holds a whole sub-sequence of real top-of-book changes. A merge floor that admits every distinct `(source_ts, content)` orders two publishers inside one tick by **arrival**, which per-publisher network delay corrupts (the `hl-bbo-feed-race` board shows inter-feed skew >100 ms). Concretely, on a falling price:\r\n\r\n```\r\ntick T, leader A observes:  5 @ t=.25,  4 @ t=.5,  3 @ t=.75\r\n        laggard B observes:                3.9 @ t=.6   (delay +.3 -> arrives after A's 3)\r\narrival order: 5, 4, 3, 3.9  ->  consumer's latest = 3.9, a phantom uptick\r\n```\r\n\r\n`3.9` was observed *before* A's `3` but arrives last, so merge serves a stale value as the freshest. Arrival order != observation order, and the only trustworthy ordering is within a single source. Latch-to-leader emits A's `5, 4, 3` and drops B's `3.9` -> monotonic, fresh, no phantom tick.\r\n\r\n## Validation on live two-publisher captures\r\n\r\nPulled real TYO windows from the recorder S3 warehouse (`mainnet-beta/aws-tyo-mn-recorder1-…`) and simulated merge vs latch + publisher divergence (`examples/tick_analysis.rs`, kept local / not committed):\r\n\r\n| metric | 120s fixture | peak hour (50 files, 1.8M quotes) | calm hour (267k frames) |\r\n|---|---|---|---|\r\n| latch drops (of merge) | 0.36% | 0.16% | 1.14% |\r\n| resting-state diff | 0.38% of ticks | 0.19% | 1.26% |\r\n| leader undersampled | 0.045% of ticks | 0.053% | 0.060% |\r\n| publisher B present | — | 95% | 99% |\r\n| only-A unique content | — | 0.12% | 0.03% |\r\n| decode errors | 0 | 0 | 0 |\r\n\r\nThe genuinely-ambiguous case (leader undersampled — leader emitted fewer distinct contents than the laggard at a tick) is flat at **~0.05% of ticks** across calm/peak/volatility. Even when a leader under samples, if it's arriving faster, it's better than more stale data. The higher resting-diff in the calm hour is latch *correctly* dropping more delay-corrupted non-leader samples (publishers overlap 90% of calm ticks vs 72% at peak), not errors. Publisher B (`148.51.123.3`, gcp-tyo) is consistently dominant; A (`148.51.120.79`, aws-tyo) is a near-subset (≤0.12% unique) — latch's adaptive per-tick leader selection handles this without hardcoding a primary.\r\n\r\n## Tests\r\n- **Unit** (`arbiter` + `processor`): pin the false-uptick scenario directly — the leader emits its in-order series, a non-leader's sample at the same tick is dropped.\r\n- **Two-publisher integration** (`tests/dedup.rs`) on `tob_btc_dual.combined.bin` (both publishers interleaved in capture order): `no_business_duplicates`, quotes non-decreasing in `source_ts`, emitted count 4468. Plus `per_symbol_dedup_is_independent` (busy BTC doesn't perturb quiet DOGE).\r\n- Single-publisher e2e contract unchanged (41 quotes — latch is a no-op with one publisher).\r\n- Gates green: `cargo +nightly fmt --check`, `cargo clippy --all-targets -Dwarnings`, `cargo test --lib` (52), `--test e2e` (8), `--test dedup` (2).\r\n\r\n## Out of scope\r\n- **MBO depth dedup** — per-publisher book reconstruction + depth duplicate-identity + the `emit_depth` `source_ts` collision: tracked in **#28** (its identity problem is genuinely different — the oracle's depth key carries no book content).\r\n- The distinct-source-IP *live socket* path isn't exercised in CI (loopback-sourced multicast doesn't reach a default-interface join, and a second eth0 IP needs NET_ADMIN); the dedup is validated in-process with controlled source IPs, and `datagram_src_ip` extraction is unit-tested.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0e0cfeb0-baf3-4b7d-9735-46f33d7f33c8","uuid":"06a49ed3-3d55-4d0b-b279-604e116c1fba","timestamp":"2026-06-18T03:08:07.441Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"TITLE: Multi-publisher TOB dedup (source-IP demux + windowed-identity)\nBASE: bdz/tob-pcap-fixtures\nHEAD: bdz/multi-publisher-dedup de61ad58f0268480853948599e468a6b8784926c\nUPDATED: 2026-06-18T02:54:13Z\n---BODY---\n## Summary\r\n\r\nMulti-publisher **Top-of-Book** deduplication: when several independent publishers mirror the same feed onto one multicast group, re-serve each logical update once, coherently ordered. **Stacked on #23** (base `bdz/tob-pcap-fixtures`); rebase to `main` once that merges. MBO depth dedup is tracked separately in #28.\r\n\r\n## What's included\r\n\r\n- **Source-IP demux.** The datagram source address (from `recvmsg`) is surfaced as `FrameCtx.publisher`. Stock publishers all use `channel_id = 0` with no per-publisher wire field, so source IP is the demux key (confirmed with the feed team).\r\n- **Per-source-IP `SeqTracker`.** Keyed by source IP so a slower publisher's frames aren't cross-dropped as \"stale\" before dedup runs.\r\n- **Quotes — latch-to-leader floor** (`src/ingest/arbiter.rs`, `StalenessFloor<K,V,P>`): per `(venue, symbol)`, within one `source_ts` tick emit only the *leader* (first publisher to open the tick) and drop other publishers' samples at that `source_ts`; re-select the leader each new tick. Also drops a strictly-older BBO (stale laggard) and the leader's exact `(source_ts, content)` repeats. Output `source_ts` is non-decreasing; within a tick the series is one publisher's coherent, in-order subsequence.\r\n- **Trades — windowed `trade_id` dedup** (`WindowedDedup`): a point-in-time event, so a competing publisher's copy / in-window reorder is dropped but every distinct print is kept.\r\n\r\n## Why latch-to-leader (not a merge floor)\r\n\r\nHL stamps `source_ts` coarsely — block-granular, up to ~376 distinct BBOs share one `source_ts` — so a tick holds a whole sub-sequence of real top-of-book changes. A merge floor that admits every distinct `(source_ts, content)` orders two publishers inside one tick by **arrival**, which per-publisher network delay corrupts (the `hl-bbo-feed-race` board shows inter-feed skew >100 ms). Concretely, on a falling price:\r\n\r\n```\r\ntick T, leader A observes:  5 @ t=.25,  4 @ t=.5,  3 @ t=.75\r\n        laggard B observes:                3.9 @ t=.6   (delay +.3 -> arrives after A's 3)\r\narrival order: 5, 4, 3, 3.9  ->  consumer's latest = 3.9, a phantom uptick\r\n```\r\n\r\n`3.9` was observed *before* A's `3` but arrives last, so merge serves a stale value as the freshest. Arrival order != observation order, and the only trustworthy ordering is within a single source. Latch-to-leader emits A's `5, 4, 3` and drops B's `3.9` -> monotonic, fresh, no phantom tick.\r\n\r\n## Validation on live two-publisher captures\r\n\r\nPulled real TYO windows from the recorder S3 warehouse (`mainnet-beta/aws-tyo-mn-recorder1-…`) and simulated merge vs latch + publisher divergence (`examples/tick_analysis.rs`, kept local / not committed):\r\n\r\n| metric | 120s fixture | peak hour (50 files, 1.8M quotes) | calm hour (267k frames) |\r\n|---|---|---|---|\r\n| latch drops (of merge) | 0.36% | 0.16% | 1.14% |\r\n| resting-state diff | 0.38% of ticks | 0.19% | 1.26% |\r\n| leader undersampled | 0.045% of ticks | 0.053% | 0.060% |\r\n| publisher B present | — | 95% | 99% |\r\n| only-A unique content | — | 0.12% | 0.03% |\r\n| decode errors | 0 | 0 | 0 |\r\n\r\nThe genuinely-ambiguous case (leader undersampled — leader emitted fewer distinct contents than the laggard at a tick) is flat at **~0.05% of ticks** across calm/peak/volatility. Even when a leader under samples, if it's arriving faster, it's better than more stale data. The higher resting-diff in the calm hour is latch *correctly* dropping more delay-corrupted non-leader samples (publishers overlap 90% of calm ticks vs 72% at peak), not errors. Publisher B (`148.51.123.3`, gcp-tyo) is consistently dominant; A (`148.51.120.79`, aws-tyo) is a near-subset (≤0.12% unique) — latch's adaptive per-tick leader selection handles this without hardcoding a primary.\r\n\r\n## Tests\r\n- **Unit** (`arbiter` + `processor`): pin the false-uptick scenario directly — the leader emits its in-order series, a non-leader's sample at the same tick is dropped.\r\n- **Two-publisher integration** (`tests/dedup.rs`) on `tob_btc_dual.combined.bin` (both publishers interleaved in capture order): `no_business_duplicates`, quotes non-decreasing in `source_ts`, emitted count 4468. Plus `per_symbol_dedup_is_independent` (busy BTC doesn't perturb quiet DOGE).\r\n- Single-publisher e2e contract unchanged (41 quotes — latch is a no-op with one publisher).\r\n- Gates green: `cargo +nightly fmt --check`, `cargo clippy --all-targets -Dwarnings`, `cargo test --lib` (52), `--test e2e` (8), `--test dedup` (2).\r\n\r\n## Out of scope\r\n- **MBO depth dedup** — per-publisher book reconstruction + depth duplicate-identity + the `emit_depth` `source_ts` collision: tracked in **#28** (its identity problem is genuinely different — the oracle's depth key carries no book content).\r\n- The distinct-source-IP *live socket* path isn't exercised in CI (loopback-sourced multicast doesn't reach a default-interface join, and a second eth0 IP needs NET_ADMIN); the dedup is validated in-process with controlled source IPs, and `datagram_src_ip` extraction is unit-tested.","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
